<div class="page-header"><h1>Change careers without breaking the bank</h1>
<p>ACC is not just for recent high school graduates. It serves working adults changing careers, upgrading skills, or earning certifications. In-district rates make that affordable. Out-of-district rates price many people out.</p></div>
<div class="prose">
<h2>Short-term credentials that lead to jobs</h2>
<p>Not every career change requires a two-year degree. ACC offers Occupational Skills Awards (9-14 credit hours) that provide workforce training leading directly to job entry. Students do not need to meet TSI requirements to enroll. At in-district rates, a 12-credit-hour credential costs $1,020. At out-of-district rates, it costs $3,432. Source: <a href="https://catalog.austincc.edu/award-plans/degrees-and-certificates-listing-by-award-type/" target="_blank">ACC Awards Listing</a>.</p>
<p>ACC also offers institutional certificates (under 15 credit hours) and longer certificate programs in fields like welding, HVAC, cybersecurity, medical lab technology, and more.</p>

<h2>Evening, weekend, and online options</h2>
<p>ACC offers classes across 11 Central Texas campuses plus a full suite of online courses. Many workforce programs are designed around working adult schedules, with evening and weekend options. ACC Online offers fully online degrees and certificate programs.</p>

<h2>The state invests more in adult learners</h2>
<p>Texas HB 8 (2023) provides a 50% additional funding weight for adult learners age 25 and older. This means the state incentivizes community colleges to expand programs serving working adults. ACC benefits from this funding when it graduates adult learners with credentials, creating a direct alignment between state policy and the campaign's case for access. Source: <a href="https://www.highered.texas.gov/community-college-finance/formula-funding/" target="_blank">THECB Formula Funding</a>.</p>

<h2>What does the research say?</h2>
<p>A Texas-based estimate from researcher Jeffrey Denning finds that community college enrollment increases by approximately 5.1 percentage points per $1,000 decrease in tuition. For Pflugerville, where the per-credit reduction would be $201 ($6,030/year for full-time), this suggests a substantial enrollment response among adults who were previously priced out. Source: <a href="https://www.sole-jole.org/assets/docs/15041.pdf" target="_blank">Denning, SOLE/JOLE</a>.</p>

<h2>Seniors (65+): free tuition is already available</h2>
<p>Texas residents age 65 or older can take up to 6 credit hours per semester at ACC with tuition waived, on a space-available basis. This benefit applies regardless of in-district status. But in-district seniors avoid the $201/credit hour out-of-district fee, and they receive the $75,000 additional homestead exemption plus the tax ceiling. Source: <a href="https://admissions.austincc.edu/tuition-costs/tuition-waivers-and-exemptions/" target="_blank">ACC Tuition Waivers</a>.</p>

<div class="callout"><strong>You do not have to quit your job to change your career.</strong> ACC's flexible scheduling, online options, and short-term certificates are designed for people who work full-time and have families. In-district pricing makes the decision about time, not money.</div>
